  "prompt": "How do I calculate the water-cement ratio for concrete?",
  "response": "To calculate the water-cement ratio for concrete, follow these steps:\n\n1. Determine the total water content in the mix (in kg or liters)\n\n2. Determine the total cement content in the mix (in kg)\n\n3. Use the formula: Water-Cement Ratio = Weight of Water / Weight of Cement\n\nExample:\n- If you have 200 kg of water\n- And 400 kg of cement\n- Water-Cement Ratio = 200/400 = 0.50\n\nImportant considerations:\n- Typical water-cement ratios range from 0.35 to 0.60\n- Lower ratios generally result in stronger concrete\n- Higher ratios improve workability but reduce strength\n- The ratio depends on desired concrete strength and application\n- Consider environmental conditions and specific project requirements\n\nFactors affecting water-cement ratio:\n- Strength requirements\n- Exposure conditions\n- Type of cement\n- Aggregate characteristics\n- Desired workability\n\nAlways consult local building codes and engineering standards for specific guidance.",
